post_text:
Parents and Guardians,

As part of our reopening plan and commitment to keeping our students and staff healthy, we are requiring all families to submit a daily self-assessment for each one of their children. Each staff member and visitor to the school will also be required to complete a daily self-assessment before entering the building.

You can access the Daily Student Self-Assessment here: https://www.clydesavannah.org/domain/75

The assessment can also be found under the News section on the District homepage.

Thank you for your continued support and understanding during this unique time.

post_text: Virtual Summer Reading Starts this WEEK through 21st Century!
shared_text:
Clyde-Savannah Team Library
July 5 at 12:44 PM ·

Virtual Summer Reading Starts this WEEK through 21st Century!

Join Miss Marr and Mrs. Wood (6th Grade ELA Teacher) as we read together the FANTASTIC chapter book, "The One and Only Ivan" by Katherine Applegate on Tuesdays at 12pm. Students will listen to the story each week, answer comprehension questions, and play some games. This is geared for 3 grade and up. To join the fun, go to Google Meet and type Ivan as the meeting code.

Join Miss Marr Thursday evenings at 7pm for Summer Storytime! We will read some stories, learn some facts, and have some fun! To join the storytime, head to Google Meet and type the code Storytime. This will be geared towards UPK-2nd grade but anyone is welcome to come listen!

Email Miss Marr (courtney.marr@clydesavannah.org) or contact Erin Church with any questions.

Keep Learning, Keep Exploring, and Keep Reading!

post_text:
To provide feedback on your feelings on school reopening, please complete the initial questions in this survey.
https://www.surveygizmo.com/s3/5657688/Parent-Voice-Survey-2020

The initial feedback on school reopening will take less than two minutes, and the survey as a whole will take less than five minutes. Your survey will help us gather insight and understanding first on your perspective on reopening school and then on the impact of virtual learning over the past few months.

While guidance from NYS and directives from our own local Public Health Department are governing forces in our decision making, we would like to make sure that we are as inclusive and as sensitive as we can be to the needs of the families we serve.

Data is being collected by Evalumetrics Research in partnership with Finger Lakes Community Schools and any questions may be directed to jroscup@flxcommunityschools.org; each district will receive a copy of their own data. Each district will also receive a copy of the county data for comparison.

post_text:
Attention Clyde-Savannah Families:

The district will be collecting district-issued devices (Chromebooks, iPads, chargers, Kajeets, and graphing calculators) on Tuesday, June 16, 2020, from 3-7 PM, in the MS/HS parking lot. This will give the technology department an opportunity to complete necessary updates to the devices over the summer. If your son or daughter is enrolled in a summer program, please hang on to his or her device. Those will be collected at the end of program later in the summer.

When you arrive, you will be directed to large grade-level boxes lining the pavement, from the parking lot to the Field House and through the transportation lot, where you can place your devices. Please be sure to remember your mask. Devices will be placed directly in the boxes to adhere to social distancing guidelines.

If your son or daughter did not pick up his or her locker belongings last month, please expect to pick those up from the Field House during this time.

Thank you for your continued support and patience during this unprecedented time in our lives.

post_text:
Dear Clyde-Savannah Families:

As we begin to approach the “end of the year,” many are inquiring about when the last day of school for students will be. As of right now, we are anticipating the last day for students will be Monday, June 15. With that said, please be advised that this Friday, May 22 will be a day of instruction to meet our continuity of learning expectations and state requirements for student instructional days. Please be advised that Monday, May 25 is Memorial Day, and will not be a day for Continuity of Instruction/Learning. The District Leadership Team will be working to develop processes and communications for staff, students, and families on what will be needed to close out the year. This information will be communicated in the next few weeks.

Sincerely,
Michael C. Hayden, Superintendent

post_text: We are so excited to recognize our senior class with banners! Thank you to everyone in our community who made this possible! #BetterTogether
shared_text:
Village of Clyde, NY
April 26 at 1:34 PM ·

The village of Clyde is excited to let the seniors and their parents know that we have formed a partnership with Clyde-Savannah Central School and purchased banners for each of them. We hope for them to be delivered and hung on the light poles in our main street area (Savannah students in Savannah) in just a few weeks. Special thank you to the Town of Savannah,for allowing us to hang the Savannah students there, Larry Lang, Craig Pawlak , Mike Hayden, Jill Robert, Kris King, and Jen Peeso for their help. If I missed anyone I’m sorry in advance. Lol. A big thank you to my village board for listening and believing in something I felt strongly about with me.

post_text: Times are tough right now, but the Clyde-Savannah community is as strong as ever. Staff have volunteered to hand out meals and instructional materials. Parents are figuring out how to help their children learn from home. Students and teachers are communicating with each other in new ways while trying to maintain a level of normalcy. We're in this together, and we're #BetterTogether. Even though we can't physically be together right now, we hope you'll support the Clyde-Savannah community on Facebook by adding our Better Together frame to your profile picture. To add the frame, click on your profile picture, then "add frame", and seach "Clyde-Savannah Better Together."

post_text:
Despite the closure, the Elementary School is staying connected through Facebook! Every weekday, Mrs. Lumb goes live on the Clyde-Savannah Elementary School page at 1 p.m. Elementary students and their families are invited to watch as Mrs. Lumb announces birthdays, tells hilarious jokes, reads a story, and more! The Elementary page also has its own spirit days (sunglasses day, purple and gold day, etc.), and posts fun challenges that students can try at home.

Check out the video to see some of the great photos our students and staff have posted on the Elementary page!

shared_text:
Clyde-Savannah Schools
March 16 at 9:13 PM ·

INFORMATION ON PICK-UP OF STUDENT MATERIALS:

Please be advised that the District will be implementing the following plan tomorrow (3/17) for pick-up of student materials. This will include chromebooks for grades 6-12, musical instruments and medications as necessary.

Pick-up times will be from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. in the gymnasium of each building. We urge you not to report to the school if you are sick. Please arrange for someone else to pick up materials if that is the case.

During tomorrow’s pick-up times, students and parents will not be allowed to retrieve items from school lockers. The District will notify families when they can retrieve these items at a later date.

Also, please be reminded that the meal distribution will begin on Wednesday, March 18.

Once again, I can’t thank the Clyde-Savannah school community enough for your patience, flexibility and teamwork for getting through this very difficult situation.

Sincerely,
Michael C. Hayden, Superintendent

Please be advised that the District will be implementing the following plan tomorrow (3/17) for pick-up of student materials. This will include chromebooks for grades 6-12, musical instruments and medications as necessary.

Pick-up times will be from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. in the gymnasium of each building. We urge you not to report to the school if you are sick. Please arrange for someone else to pick up materials if that is the case.

During tomorrow’s pick-up times, students and parents will not be allowed to retrieve items from school lockers. The District will notify families when they can retrieve these items at a later date.

Also, please be reminded that the meal distribution will begin on Wednesday, March 18.

Once again, I can’t thank the Clyde-Savannah school community enough for your patience, flexibility and teamwork for getting through this very difficult situation.

Sincerely,
Michael C. Hayden, Superintendent

Dear Clyde-Savannah Families:

Please be advised that as a result of new federal guidelines relating to the coronavirus, and for the safety and well-being of our school community, Clyde-Savannah Central School District will be closed tomorrow, March 17. We will remain closed through April 13. Please continue to monitor our website and social media for more information regarding distribution of learning materials for students. It is our goal to have this information communicated by tomorrow morning. Once again, thank you for your continued patience and flexibility during this rapidly evolving situation.

Sincerely,
Michael C. Hayden, Superintendent

post_text: Don't forget to donate blood today!
shared_text:
Clyde-Savannah Schools
December 13, 2019 at 5:00 PM ·

Consider donating blood on Monday at our blood drive. The blood drive is open to adults and students. Things to remember if you decide to donate:

1. You need to bring your ID with you.

2. Students who are 16 years old also need to bring the signed parent consent form.

3. You need to be in good health.

4. Get at least 8 hours of sleep the night before.

5. Eat a healthy breakfast, lunch or both if your appointment in later in the day.

6. Drink extra water or fluids in the days leading up to and including the day of your donation.

shared_text:
Brian Manktelow NY State Assembly 130th district
November 7, 2019 at 2:41 PM ·

Earlier this week I had a good conversation with Clyde-Savannah School Superintendent Mike Hayden as part of my effort to see all of the town supervisors, village mayors and school superintendents in my district before I return to Albany. Clyde-Savannah is embarking on the construction of a new pool that is regulation size, instead of the smaller pool the district has now -- which is too small to allow swim competitions to be help locally. Other programs that are innovative were also discussed.
